ğŸ”¹ PUT vs PATCH (What the HTTP spec says)
âœ… PUT (Replace the resource)

Semantics: replace the entire resource

Client is supposed to send the full representation

Missing fields may be considered removed or reset

âœ… PATCH (Partial update)

Semantics: update only the provided fields

Unsent fields remain unchanged

ğŸ“˜ This is what REST / HTTP standards say.

ğŸ”¹ Why in Rails PUT behaves like PATCH
ğŸ‘‰ Rails does NOT enforce PUT semantics

In Rails:

PUT   /users/:id  â†’ users#update
PATCH /users/:id  â†’ users#update


Both go to the same controller action:

def update
  @user.update(user_params)
end


Rails only updates attributes you permit and send.

ğŸ” Example (Rails behavior)
Request
PUT /users/1
{
  "user": {
    "name": "John"
  }
}

What Rails does
@user.update(name: "John")


ğŸ‘‰ Email, age, etc. remain unchanged
ğŸ‘‰ Rails treats it like PATCH

ğŸ§  Why nothing â€œbreaksâ€ with PUT in Rails

Because:

ActiveRecord update performs a partial update

Missing attributes are ignored, not nulled

Strong parameters prevent mass replacement

Rails optimizes for developer safety, not strict REST purity.

ğŸ”¥ Important Interview Insight

PUT vs PATCH difference is contractual, not technical.

Rails allows PUT to behave like PATCH because:

Full replacement is risky

Clients often donâ€™t have full state

Partial updates are safer

â— When PUT would behave differently

PUT behaves like a full replacement only if you implement it that way:

def update
  @user.assign_attributes(default_attributes)
  @user.assign_attributes(user_params)
  @user.save
end


OR if your API explicitly nullifies missing fields.

Rails does not do this by default.

